<h1>Problem 292 - 2003 IMO, P6 of 6, N</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 9</h2>
<p>Let \(p\) be a prime number. Prove that there exists a prime number \(q\) such that for every integer \(n,\) the number \(n^{p} - p\) is not divisible by \(q.\)</p>
